This dosage form is generally for external application to the skin or mucous membranes. Note: A semisolid is not pourable; it does not flow or conform to its container at room temperature. It does not flow at low shear stress and generally exhibits plastic flow behavior. (NCI)

label: Dentifrice Paste Dosage Form
definition: A paste formulation intended to clean and/or polish the teeth, and which may contain certain additional agents. (NCI)

label: Pastille Dosage Form
definition: An aromatic preparation, often with a pleasing flavor, usually intended to dissolve in the mouth. (FDA)

label: Patch Dosage Form
definition: A drug delivery system that often contains an adhesive backing that is usually applied to an external site on the body.  Its ingredients either passively diffuse from, or are actively transported from, some portion of the patch.  Depending upon the patch, the ingredients are either delivered to the outer surface of the body or into the body.  A patch is sometimes synonymous with the terms Extended Release Film and System. (NCI)

label: Extended Release Patch Dosage Form
definition: A drug delivery system in the form of a patch that releases the drug in such a manner that a reduction in dosing frequency compared to that drug presented as a conventional dosage form (e.g., a solution or a prompt drug-releasing, conventional solid dosage form). (NCI)

label: Electrically Controlled Extended Release Patch Dosage Form
pref_label: Electrically Controlled Extended Release Patch Dosage Form
definition: A drug delivery system in the form of a patch which is controlled by an electric current that releases the drug in such a manner that a reduction in dosing frequency compared to that drug presented as a conventional dosage form (e.g., a solution or a prompt drug-releasing, conventional solid dosage form). (NCI)

label: Pellet Dosage Form
definition: A small sterile solid mass consisting of a highly purified drug (with or without excipients) made by the formation of granules, or by compression and molding. (NCI)

label: Implantable Pellet Dosage Form
definition: A small sterile solid mass consisting of a highly purified drug (with or without excipients) made by the formation of granules, or by compression and molding; they are intended for implantation in the body (usually subcutaneously) for the purpose of providing continuous release of the drug over long periods of time. (NCI)

label: Extended Release Coated Pellets Dosage Form
pref_label: Extended Release Coated Pellets Dosage Form
definition: A solid dosage form in which the drug itself is in the form of granules to which varying amounts of coating have been applied, and which releases a drug (or drugs) in such a manner to allow a reduction in dosing frequency as compared to that drug (or drugs) presented as a conventional dosage form. (NCI)

label: Pill Dosage Form
definition: A dose of medicine in the form of a small pellet. (NCI)

label: Plaster Dosage Form
definition: Substance intended for external application made of such materials and of such consistency as to adhere to the skin and attach to a dressing; plasters are intended to afford protection and support and/or to furnish an occlusion and macerating action and to bring medication into close contact with the skin. (NCI)

label: Poultice Dosage Form
definition: A soft, moist mass of meal, herbs, seed, etc., usually applied hot in cloth that consists of gruel-like consistency. (NCI)

label: Powder Dosage Form
definition: An intimate mixture of dry, finely divided drugs and/or chemicals that may be intended for internal or external use. (NCI)

label: Dentifrice Powder Dosage Form
definition: A powder formulation intended to clean and/or polish the teeth, and which may contain certain additional agents. (NCI)

label: Powder for Solution Dosage Form
definition: An intimate mixture of dry, finely divided drugs and/or chemicals, which, upon the addition of suitable vehicles, yields a solution. (NCI)

label: Powder for Suspension Dosage Form
definition: An intimate mixture of dry, finely divided drugs and/or chemicals, which, upon the addition of suitable vehicles, yields a suspension (a liquid preparation containing the solid particles dispersed in the liquid vehicle). (NCI)

label: Metered Powder Dosage Form
definition: A powder dosage form that is situated inside a container that has a mechanism to deliver a specified quantity. (NCI)

label: Ring Dosage Form
definition: A small circular object with a vacant circular center that is usually intended to be placed in the body by special inserters, where the medication is released, generally for localized effects. (FDA)

label: Rinse Dosage Form
definition: A liquid used to cleanse by flushing. (NCI)

label: Salve Dosage Form
definition: A thick ointment or cerate (a fat or wax based preparation with a consistency between an ointment and a plaster). (NCI)

label: Shampoo Dosage Form
definition: A liquid soap or detergent used to clean the hair and scalp and is often used as a vehicle for dermatologic agents. (NCI)

label: Shampoo Suspension Dosage Form
definition: A liquid soap or detergent containing one or more solid, insoluble substances dispersed in a liquid vehicle that is used to clean the hair and scalp and is often used as a vehicle for dermatologic agents. (NCI)

label: Soap Dosage Form
definition: Any compound of one or more fatty acids, or their equivalents, with an alkali; soap is detergent and is much employed in liniments, enemas, and in making pills. It is also a mild aperient, antacid and antiseptic. (NCI)

label: Solution Dosage Form
definition: A clear, homogeneous liquid dosage form that contains one or more chemical substances dissolved in a solvent or mixture of mutually miscible solvents. Note: A liquid is pourable; it flows and conforms to its container at room temperature. It displays Newtonian or pseudoplastic flow behavior. (NCI)

label: Concentrate for Solution Dosage Form
definition: A liquid preparation (i.e., a substance that flows readily in its natural state) that contains a drug dissolved in a suitable solvent or mixture of mutually miscible solvents; the drug has been strengthened by the evaporation of its non-active parts. (NCI)

label: Solution For Slush Dosage Form
definition: A solution for the preparation of an iced saline slush, which is administered by irrigation and used to induce regional hypothermia (in conditions such as certain open heart and kidney surgical procedures) by its direct application. (NCI)

label: Gel Forming Drops Solution Dosage Form
pref_label: Gel Forming Drops Solution Dosage Form
definition: A solution, which after usually being administered in a drop-wise fashion, forms a gel. (FDA)

label: Extended Release Gel Forming Solution Dosage Form
pref_label: Extended Release Gel Forming Solution Dosage Form
definition: A solution that forms a gel when it comes in contact with ocular fluid, and which allows at least a reduction in dosing frequency

label: Drops Solution Dosage Form
definition: A solution which is usually administered in a drop-wise fashion. (FDA)

label: Sponge Dosage Form
definition: A porous, interlacing, absorbent material that contains a drug.  It is typically used for applying or introducing medication, or for cleansing.  A sponge usually retains its shape.(FDA)

label: Spray Dosage Form
definition: A liquid minutely divided as by a jet of air or steam. (NCI)

label: Metered Spray Dosage Form
definition: A non-pressurized dosage form consisting of valves which allow the dispensing of a specified quantity of spray upon each activation. (NCI)

label: Spray Suspension Dosage Form
definition: A liquid preparation containing solid particles dispersed in a liquid vehicle and in the form of coarse droplets or as finely divided solids to be applied locally, most usually to the nasal-pharyngeal tract, or topically to the skin. (NCI)

label: Stick Dosage Form
definition: A dosage form prepared in a relatively long and slender often cylindrical form. (NCI)

label: Strip Dosage Form
definition: A long narrow piece of material.

label: Suppository Dosage Form
definition: A solid body of various weights and shapes, adapted for introduction into the rectal, vaginal, or urethral orifice of the human body; they usually melt, soften, or dissolve at body temperature. (NCI)

label: Extended Release Suppository Dosage Form
definition: A drug delivery system in the form of a suppository that allows at least a reduction in dosing frequency. (NCI)

label: Suspension Dosage Form
definition: A liquid dosage form that contains solid particles dispersed in a liquid vehicle. Note: A liquid is pourable; it flows and conforms to its container at room temperature. It displays Newtonian or pseudoplastic flow behavior.(FDA)

label: Extended Release Suspension Dosage Form
definition: A liquid preparation consisting of solid particles dispersed throughout a liquid phase in which the particles are not soluble; the suspension has been formulated in a manner to allow at least a reduction in dosing frequency as compared to that drug presented as a conventional dosage form (e.g., as a solution or a prompt drug-releasing, conventional solid dosage form). (NCI)

label: Drops Suspension Dosage Form
definition: A suspension which is usually administered in a dropwise fashion. (FDA)

label: Suture Dosage Form
definition: A strand or fiber used to hold wound edges in apposition during healing. (NCI)

label: Swab Dosage Form
definition: A small piece of relatively flat absorbent material that contains a drug.  A swab may also be attached to one end of a small stick.  A swab is typically used for applying medication or for cleansing. (NCI)

label: Syrup Dosage Form
definition: An oral solution containing high concentrations of sucrose or other sugars; the term has also been used to include any other liquid dosage form prepared in a sweet and viscid vehicle, including oral suspensions.  (NCI)

label: Tablet Dosage Form
definition: A solid dosage form containing medicinal substances with or without suitable diluents.  (NCI)

label: Chewable Tablet Dosage Form
definition: A solid dosage form containing medicinal substances with or without suitable diluents that is intended to be chewed, producing a pleasant tasting residue in the oral cavity that is easily swallowed and does not leave a bitter or unpleasant after-taste. (NCI)

label: Coated Tablet Dosage Form
definition: A solid dosage form that contains medicinal substances with or without suitable diluents and is covered with a designated coating. (NCI)

label: Tablet Coated Particles Dosage Form
definition: A solid dosage form containing a conglomerate of medicinal particles that have each been covered with a coating. (FDA)

label: Delayed Release Tablet Dosage Form
definition: A solid dosage form which releases a drug (or drugs) at a time other than promptly after administration. Enteric-coated articles are delayed release dosage forms. (NCI)

label: Delayed Release Particles Tablet Dosage Form
pref_label: Delayed Release Particles Tablet Dosage Form
definition: A solid dosage form containing a conglomerate of medicinal particles that have been covered with a coating which releases a drug (or drugs) at a time other than promptly after administration. Enteric-coated articles are delayed release dosage forms.  (NCI)

label: Effervescent Tablet Dosage Form
definition: A solid dosage form containing mixtures of acids (e.g., citric acid, tartaric acid) and sodium bicarbonate, which release carbon dioxide when dissolved in water; it is intended to be dissolved or dispersed in water before administration.(FDA)

label: Extended Release Tablet Dosage Form
definition: A solid dosage form containing a drug which allows at least a reduction in dosing frequency as compared to that drug presented in conventional dosage form. (NCI)

label: Film Coated Tablet Dosage Form
definition: A solid dosage form that contains medicinal substances with or without suitable diluents and is coated with a thin layer of a water-insoluble or water-soluble polymer. (NCI)

label: Film Coated Extended Release Tablet Dosage Form
pref_label: Film Coated Extended Release Tablet Dosage Form
definition: A solid dosage form that contains medicinal substances with or without suitable diluents and is coated with a thin layer of a water-insoluble or water-soluble polymer; the tablet is formulated in such manner as to make the contained medicament available over an extended period of time following ingestion. (NCI)

label: Tablet For Solution Dosage Form
definition: A tablet that forms a solution when placed in a liquid. (FDA)

label: Tablet For Suspension Dosage Form
definition: A tablet that forms a suspension when placed in a liquid (formerly referred to as a Dispersible Tablet).

label: Multilayered Tablet Dosage Form
definition: A solid dosage form containing medicinal substances that have been compressed to form a multiple-layered tablet or a tablet-within-a-tablet, the inner tablet being the core and the outer portion being the shell. (NCI)

label: Multilayered Extended Release Tablet Dosage Form
pref_label: Multilayered Extended Release Tablet Dosage Form
definition: A solid dosage form containing medicinal substances that have been compressed to form a multiple-layered tablet or a tablet-within-a-tablet, the inner tablet being the core and the outer portion being the shell, which, additionally, is covered in a designated coating; the tablet is formulated in such manner as to allow at least a reduction in dosing frequency as compared to that drug presented as a conventional dosage form. (NCI)

label: Orally Disintegrating Tablet Dosage Form
definition: A solid dosage form containing medicinal substances which disintegrates rapidly, usually within a matter of seconds, when placed upon the tongue.  (NCI)

label: Tablet Orally Disintegrating Delayed Release Dosage Form
pref_label: Tablet Orally Disintegrating Delayed Release Dosage Form
definition: A solid dosage form containing medicinal substances which disintegrates rapidly, usually within a matter of seconds, when placed upon the tongue, but which releases a drug (or drugs) at a time other than promptly after administration. (FDA)

label: Soluble Tablet Dosage Form
definition: A solid dosage form that contains medicinal substances with or without suitable diluents and possesses the ability to dissolve in fluids. (NCI)

label: Sugar Coated Tablet Dosage Form
definition: A solid dosage form that contains medicinal substances with or without suitable diluents and is coated with a colored or an uncolored water-soluble sugar. (NCI)

label: Tampon Dosage Form
definition: A plug made of cotton, sponge, or oakum variously used in surgery to plug the nose, vagina, etc., for the control of hemorrhage or the absorption of secretions. (NCI)

label: Tape Dosage Form
definition: A narrow woven fabric, or a narrow extruded synthetic (such as plastic), usually with an adhesive on one or both sides. (NCI)

label: Tincture Dosage Form
definition: An alcoholic or hydroalcoholic solution prepared from vegetable materials or from chemical substances.  (NCI)

label: Troche Dosage Form
definition: A discoid-shaped solid containing the medicinal agent in a suitably flavored base; troches are placed in the mouth where they slowly dissolve, liberating the active ingredients.  (NCI)

label: Unassigned Dosage Form
definition: A dosage form has yet to be assigned.  (NCI)

label: Wafer Dosage Form
definition: A thin slice of material containing a medicinal agent.  (NCI)

label: Completion/Reason for Non-Completion
pref_label: CDISC SDTM Reason for Non-Completion Terminology
definition: The reason that a subject was discontinued from a clinical trial.

label: Adverse Event
definition: Any untoward medical occurrence in a patient or clinical investigation subject administered a pharmaceutical product and which does not necessarily have a causal relationship with this treatment. An adverse event (AE) can therefore be any unintended sign (including an abnormal laboratory finding), symptom,or disease temporally associated with the use of a medicinal (investigational) product, whether or not related to the medicinal (investigational) product. NOTE: For further information, see the ICH Guideline for Clinical Safety Data Management: Definitions and Standards for Expedited Reporting. “[Modified from ICH E2A]” Synonyms: side effect, adverse experience. See also serious adverse event, serious adverse experience.  (CDISC glossary)

label: Complete
definition: To possess every necessary or normal part or component or step; having come or been brought to a conclusion. (NCI)

label: Death
definition: The absence of life or state of being dead. (NCI)

label: Lack of Efficacy
definition: The lack of expected or desired effect related to a therapy. (NCI)

label: Lost To Follow-up
definition: The loss or lack of continuation of follow-up after a study has officially closed.  See Follow-up. (NCI)

label: Non-Compliance With Study Drug
definition: An indication that a subject has not agreed with or followed the instructions related to the study medication. (NCI)

label: Other
definition: Different than the one(s) previously specified or mentioned. (NCI)

label: Physician Decision
definition: A position, opinion or judgment reached after consideration by a physician with reference to subject. (NCI)

label: Pregnancy
definition: Pregnancy is the state or condition of having a developing embryo or fetus in the body (uterus), after union of an ovum and spermatozoon, during the period from conception to birth. (NCI)

label: Progressive Disease
definition: A disease process that is increasing in scope or severity. (NCI)

label: Protocol Violation
definition: An event or decision that stands in contrast to the guidelines set out by the protocol. (NCI)

label: Recovery
definition: A healing process and/or an outcome implying relative health.  The term is typically used in the context of direct and indirect effects of sickness or injury. (NCI)

label: Trial Screen Failure
definition: The potential subject who does not meet one or more criteria required for participation in a trial.

label: Study Terminated By Sponsor
definition: An indication that a clinical study was stopped by its sponsor.  (NCI)

label: Technical Problem
definition: A problem with some technical aspect of a clinical study, usually related to an instrument.  (NCI)

label: Withdrawal by Subject
definition: An indication that a study participant has removed itself from the study.  (NCI)

label: Relation to Reference Period
pref_label: CDISC SDTM Relation to Reference Period Terminology
definition: The name of a code list that contains terms that reference timepoints within and without a defined time period.

label: Status Post
definition: The time period following a point or another period of time. (NCI)

label: Prior
definition: Earlier in time or order. (NCI)

label: During
definition: At some point in a given period of time. (NCI)

label: During Or After
definition: Within a certain period of time or after a certain point or period in time. (NCI)

label: Unknown
definition: Not known, not observed, not recorded, or refused. (NCI)

label: Route of Administration
pref_label: CDISC SDTM Route of Administration Terminology
definition: The course by which a substance was administered in order to reach the site of action in the body.

label: Auricular Route of Administration
definition: Administration to or by way of the ear.(FDA)

label: Buccal Route of Administration
definition: Administration directed toward the cheek, generally from within the mouth.(FDA)

label: Conjunctival Route of Administration
definition: Administration to the conjunctiva, the delicate membrane that lines the eyelids and covers the exposed surface of the eyeball.(FDA)

label: Cutaneous Route of Administration
definition: Administration to the skin.(FDA)

label: Dental Route of Administration
definition: Administration to a tooth or teeth.(FDA)

label: Electro-osmosis Route of Administration
definition: Administration of through the diffusion of substance through a membrane in an electric field.(FDA)

label: Endocervical Route of Administration
definition: Administration within the canal of the cervix uteri. Synonymous with the term intracervical.(FDA)

label: Endosinusial Route of Administration
definition: Administration within the nasal sinuses of the head.(FDA)

label: Endotracheal Route of Administration
definition: Administration directly into the trachea. Synonymous with the term intratracheal.(FDA)

label: Enteral Route of Administration
definition: Administration directly into the intestines.(FDA)

label: Epidural Route of Administration
definition: Administration upon or over the dura mater.(FDA)

label: Extraamniotic Route of Administration
definition: Administration to the outside of the membrane enveloping the fetus.(FDA)

label: Extracorporeal Circulation Route of Administration
definition: Administration outside of the body.(FDA)

label: Administration Via Hemodialysis
definition: Administration through hemodialysate fluid.(FDA)

label: Infiltration Route of Administration
definition: Administration that results in substances passing into tissue spaces or into cells.(FDA)

label: Interstitial Route of Administration
definition: Administration to or in the interstices of a tissue.(FDA)

label: Intraabdominal Route of Administration
definition: Administration within the abdomen.(FDA)

label: Intraamniotic Route of Administration
definition: Administration within the amnion.(FDA)

label: Intraarterial Route of Administration
definition: Administration within an artery or arteries.(FDA)

label: Intraarticular Route of Administration
definition: Administration within a joint.(FDA)

label: Intrabiliary Route of Administration
definition: Administration within the bile, bile ducts or gallbladder.(FDA)

label: Intrabronchial Route of Administration
definition: Administration within a bronchus.(FDA)

label: Intrabursal Route of Administration
definition: Administration within a bursa.(FDA)

label: Intracardiac Route of Administration
definition: Administration within the heart.(FDA)

label: Intracartilaginous Route of Administration
definition: Administration within a cartilage; endochondral.(FDA)

label: Intracaudal Route of Administration
definition: Administration within the cauda equina.(FDA)

label: Intracavernous Route of Administration
definition: Administration within a pathologic cavity, such as occurs in the lung in tuberculosis.(FDA)

label: Intracavitary Route of Administration
definition: Administration within a non-pathologic cavity, such as that of the cervix, uterus, or penis, or such as that is formed as the result of a wound.(FDA)

label: Intracerebral Route of Administration
definition: Administration within the cerebrum.(FDA)

label: Intracisternal Route of Administration
definition: Administration within the cisterna magna cerebellomedularis.(FDA)

label: Intracorneal Route of Administration
definition: Administration within the cornea (the transparent structure forming the anterior part of the fibrous tunic of the eye).(FDA)

label: Intracoronal Dental Route of Administration
definition: Administration of a drug within a portion of a tooth which is covered by enamel and which is separated from the roots by a slightly constricted region known as the neck.(FDA)

label: Intracoronary Route of Administration
definition: Administration within the coronary arteries.(FDA)

label: Intracorporus Cavernosum Route of Administration
definition: Administration within the dilatable spaces of the corporus cavernosa of the penis.(FDA)

label: Intradermal Route of Administration
definition: Administration within the dermis.(FDA)

label: Intradiscal Route of Administration
definition: Administration within a disc.(FDA)

label: Intraductal Route of Administration
definition: Administration within the duct of a gland.(FDA)

label: Intraduodenal Route of Administration
definition: Administration within the duodenum.(FDA)

label: Intradural Route of Administration
definition: Administration within or beneath the dura.(FDA)

label: Intraepidermal Route of Administration
definition: Administration within the epidermis.(FDA)

label: Intraesophageal Route of Administration
definition: Administration within the esophagus.(FDA)

label: Intragastric Route of Administration
definition: Administration within the stomach.(FDA)

label: Intragingival Route of Administration
definition: Administration within the gingivae.(FDA)

label: Intraileal Route of Administration
definition: Administration within the distal portion of the small intestine, from the jejunum to the cecum.(FDA)

label: Intralesional Route of Administration
definition: Administration within or introduced directly into a localized lesion.(FDA)

label: Intraluminal Route of Administration
definition: Administration within the lumen of a tube.(FDA)

label: Intralymphatic Route of Administration
definition: Administration within the lymph.(FDA)

label: Intramedullary Route of Administration
definition: Administration within the marrow cavity of a bone.(FDA)

label: Intrameningeal Route of Administration
definition: Administration within the meninges (the three membranes that envelope the brain and spinal cord).(FDA)

label: Intramuscular Route of Administration
definition: Administration within a muscle. (FDA)

label: Intraocular Route of Administration
definition: Administration within the eye.(FDA)

label: Intraovarian Route of Administration
definition: Administration within the ovary.(FDA)

label: Intrapericardial Route of Administration
definition: Administration within the pericardium.(FDA)

label: Intraperitoneal Route of Administration
definition: Administration within the peritoneal cavity.(FDA)

label: Intrapleural Route of Administration
definition: Administration within the pleura.(FDA)

label: Intraprostatic Route of Administration
definition: Administration within the prostate gland.(FDA)

label: Intrapulmonary Route of Administration
definition: Administration within the lungs or its bronchi.(FDA)

label: Intrasinal Route of Administration
definition: Administration within the nasal or periorbital sinuses.(FDA)

label: Intraspinal Route of Administration
definition: Administration within the vertebral column.(FDA)

label: Intrasynovial Route of Administration
definition: Administration within the synovial cavity of a joint.(FDA)

label: Intratendinous Route of Administration
definition: Administration within a tendon.(FDA)

label: Intratesticular Route of Administration
definition: Administration within the testicle.(FDA)

label: Intrathecal Route of Administration
definition: Administration within the cerebrospinal fluid at any level of the cerebrospinal axis, including injection into the cerebral ventricles.(FDA)

label: Endothoracic Route of Administration
definition: Administration within the thorax (internal to the ribs); synonymous with the term endothoracic.(FDA)

label: Intratubular Route of Administration
definition: Administration within the tubules of an organ.(FDA)

label: Intratumoral Route of Administration
definition: Administration within a tumor.(FDA)

label: Intratympanic Route of Administration
definition: Administration within the auris media.(FDA)

label: Intrauterine Route of Administration
definition: Administration within the uterus.(FDA)

label: Intravascular Route of Administration
definition: Administration within a vessel or vessels.(FDA)

label: Intravenous Route of Administration
definition: Administration within or into a vein or veins.(FDA)

label: Intravenous Bolus
definition: Administration within or into a vein or veins all at once.(FDA)

label: Intravenous Drip
definition: Administration within or into a vein or veins over a sustained period of time.(FDA)

label: Intraventricular Route of Administration
definition: Administration within a ventricle.(FDA)

label: Intravesical Route of Administration
definition: Administration within the bladder.(FDA)

label: Intravitreal Route of Administration
definition: Administration within the vitreous body of the eye.(FDA)

label: Iontophoresis Route of Administration
definition: Administration by means of an electric current where ions of soluble salts migrate into the tissues of the body.(FDA)

label: Irrigation-Route of Administration
definition: Administration to bathe or flush open wounds or body cavities.(FDA)

label: Laryngeal Route of Administration
definition: Administration directly upon the larynx.(FDA)

label: Nasal Route of Administration
definition: Administration to the nose; administered by way of the nose.(FDA)

label: Nasogastric Route of Administration
definition: Administration through the nose and into the stomach, usually by means of a tube.(FDA)

label: Route of Administration Not Applicable
definition: Routes of administration are not applicable.(FDA)

label: Occlusive Dressing Technique
definition: Administration by the topical route which is then covered by a dressing which occludes the area.(FDA)

label: Ophthalmic Route of Administration
definition: Administration to the external eye.(FDA)

label: Oral Route of Administration
definition: Administration to or by way of the mouth.(FDA)

label: Oropharyngeal Route of Administration
definition: Administration directly to the mouth and pharynx.(FDA)

label: Other Route of Administration
definition: Administration is different from others on this list.(FDA)

label: Parenteral Route of Administration
definition: Administration by injection, infusion, or implantation.(FDA)

label: Percutaneous Route of Administration
definition: Administration through the skin.(FDA)

label: Periarticular Route of Administration
definition: Administration around a joint.(FDA)

label: Peridural Route of Administration
definition: Administration to the outside of the dura mater of the spinal cord.(FDA)

label: Perineural Route of Administration
definition: Administration surrounding a nerve or nerves.(FDA)

label: Periodontal Route of Administration
definition: Administration around a tooth.(FDA)

label: Rectal Route of Administration
definition: Administration to the rectum.(FDA)

label: Inhalation Route of Administration
definition: Administration within the respiratory tract by inhaling orally or nasally for local or systemic effect.(FDA)

label: Retrobulbar Route of Administration
definition: Administration behind the pons or behind the eyeball.(FDA)

label: Soft Tissue Route Of Administration
definition: Administration into any soft tissue.(FDA)

label: Subarachnoid Route of Administration
definition: Administration beneath the arachnoid.(FDA)

label: Subconjunctival Route of Administration
definition: Administration beneath the conjunctiva.(FDA)

label: Subcutaneous Route of Administration
definition: Administration beneath the skin; hypodermic. Synonymous with the term SUBDERMAL.(FDA)

label: Sublingual Route of Administration
definition: Administration beneath the tongue.(FDA)

label: Submucosal Route of Administration
definition: Administration beneath the mucous membrane.(FDA)

label: Topical Route of Administration
definition: Administration to a particular spot on the outer surface of the body. The E2B term TRANSMAMMARY is a subset of the term TOPICAL.(FDA)

label: Transdermal Route of Administration
definition: Administration through the dermal layer of the skin to the systemic circulation by diffusion.(FDA)

label: Mucosal Route of Administration
definition: Administration across the mucosa.(FDA)

label: Transplacental Route of Administration
definition: Administration through or across the placenta.(FDA)

label: Transtracheal Route of Administration
definition: Administration through the wall of the trachea.(FDA)

label: Transtympanic Route of Administration
definition: Administration across or through the tympanic cavity.(FDA)

label: Unassigned Route of Administration
definition: Route of administration has not yet been assigned.(FDA)

label: Unknown Route of Administration
definition: Route of administration is unknown.(FDA)

label: Ureteral Route of Administration
definition: Administration into the ureter.(FDA)

label: Intraurethral Route of Administration
definition: Administration into the urethra.(FDA)

label: Vaginal Route of Administration
definition: Administration into the vagina.(FDA)

label: Severity/Intensity Scale for Adverse Events
pref_label: CDISC SDTM Severity Intensity Scale for Adverse Event Terminology
definition: A scale that defines the degree or state of disease existing in a patient as a result of the occurrence of an adverse event. (NCI)

label: Mild Adverse Event
definition: A type of adverse event that is usually transient and may require only minimal treatment or therapeutic intervention. The event does not generally interfere with usual activities of daily living.

label: Moderate Adverse Event
definition: A type of adverse event that is usually alleviated with additional specific therapeutic intervention. The event interferes with usual activities of daily living, causing discomfort but poses no significant or permanent risk of harm to the research participant.

label: Severe Adverse Event
definition: A type of adverse event that requires intensive therapeutic intervention. The event interrupts usual activities of daily living, or significantly affects clinical status. The event possesses a significant risk of harm to the research participant and hospitalization may be required.

label: Sex
pref_label: CDISC SDTM Sex of Individual Terminology
definition: The assemblage of physical properties or qualities by which male is distinguished from female; the physical difference between male and female; the distinguishing peculiarity of male or female. (NCI)

label: Female
definition: A person who belongs to the sex that normally produces ova. The term is used to indicate biological sex distinctions, or cultural gender role distinctions, or both. (NCI)

label: Male
definition: A person who belongs to the sex that normally produces sperm.  The term is used to indicate biological sex distinctions, cultural gender role distinctions, or both. (NCI)

label: Unknown
definition: Not known, not observed, not recorded, or refused. (NCI)

label: Intersex
definition: A person (one of unisexual specimens) who is born with genitalia and/or secondary sexual characteristics of indeterminate sex, or which combine features of both sexes. (NCI)

label: Sex of Participants
pref_label: CDISC SDTM Sex of Study Group Terminology
definition: The specific sex, either male, female, or mixed of the subject group being studied. (NCI)

label: Both
definition: One and the other; relating to or being two in conjunction. (NCI)

label: Female
definition: A person who belongs to the sex that normally produces ova. The term is used to indicate biological sex distinctions, or cultural gender role distinctions, or both. (NCI)

label: Male
definition: A person who belongs to the sex that normally produces sperm.  The term is used to indicate biological sex distinctions, cultural gender role distinctions, or both. (NCI)

label: Size
definition: The physical magnitude of something. (NCI)

label: Large
definition: Of considerable or relatively great size, extent, or capacity. (NCI)

label: Medium
definition: Mid-way between small and large in number, quantity, magnitude or extent. (NCI)

label: Small
definition: Limited in number, quantity, magnitude or extent. (NCI)

label: Domain Abbreviation
pref_label: CDISC SDTM Submission Domain Abbreviation Terminology
definition: A unique, 2-character domain code used in the regulatory submission process.  The domain abbreviation is used consistently throughout the submission, i.e. in the dataset name, as the value of the domain variable within the dataset, and as a prefix for most variable names in the dataset. (CDISC Glossary)

label: Analysis Dataset Domain
definition: Datasets used for statistical analysis and reporting by the sponsor. These are submitted in addition to the data tabulation datasets.

label: Adverse Event Domain
definition: Adverse events may be captured either as free text or a pre-specified list of terms.

label: Autopsy Domain
definition: Additional data about deaths, specific to findings from autopsies.

label: Bone Mineral Density Data Domain
definition: Findings resulting from evaluations of bone mineral density.

label: Biopsy Domain
definition: Findings resulting from biopsies.

label: Concomitant Medication Domain
definition: Case report form (CRF) data that captures the Concomitant and Prior Medications/Therapies used by the subject. Examples are the Concomitant Medications/Therapies given on an as needed basis and the usual Background Medications/Therapies given for a condition.

label: Comment Domain
definition: The Comments dataset accommodates two sources of comments: 1) those collected alongside other data on topical case report form (CRF) pages such as Adverse Events and 2) those collected on a separate page specifically dedicated to comments.

label: Drug Accountability Domain
definition: Data regarding the accountability of study drug, such as information on the receipt, dispensing, return, and packaging.

label: Disease Characteristics Domain
definition: Data related to the characteristics of a specific disease state under study for a subject.

label: Demographics Domain
definition: The Demographics domain includes a set of essential standard variables that describe each subject in a clinical study.  It is the parent domain for all other observations for human clinical subjects

label: Disposition Domain
definition: A subject domain utilized for the submission of information encompassing and representing data, vocabulary or records related to disposition. (NCI)

label: Protocol Deviations Domain
definition: The intent of the domain is to capture protocol violations and deviations during the course of the study and will store only those criteria violation by or deviated from by the subject and not a response to each violation or deviation.

label: Electroencephalogram Domain
definition: Findings resulting from electroencephalogram (EEG) tests.

label: Electrocardiogram Domain
definition: Findings related to the collection of ECG data, including position of the subject, method of evaluation, all cycle measurements and all findings from the ECG including an overall interpretation if collected or derived.

label: Exposure Domain
definition: The Exposure domain model records the details of a subject's exposure to protocol-specified study treatment. Study treatment may be any intervention that is prospectively defined as a test material within a study, and is typically but not always supplied to the subject.

label: Family History Domain
definition: A subject domain utilized for the submission of information encompassing and representing data, vocabulary or records related to family history. (NCI)

label: Healthcare Resource Utilization Domain
definition: Healthcare resource utilization data such as subject visits to physicians, hospitalizations, and nursing home stays.

label: Inclusion Exclusion Domain
definition: The intent of the domain model is to only collect those criteria that cause the subject to be in violation of the inclusion/exclusion criteria not a response to each criterion.

label: Laboratory Data Domain
definition: Laboratory test findings including, but is not limited to hematology, clinical chemistry and urinalysis data. This domain does not include microbiology or pharmacokinetic data, which are stored in separate domains.

label: Microbiology Specimen Domain
definition: Microbiology specimen findings, including gram stain results, and organisms found.

label: Medical History Domain
definition: The medical history dataset includes the subject's prior history at the start of the trial. Examples of subject medical history information could include general medical history, gynecological history, and primary diagnosis.

label: Meal Data Domain
definition: Information regarding the subject's meal consumption, such as fluid intake, amounts, form (solid or liquid state), frequency, etc., typically used for pharmacokinetic analysis.

label: Microbiology Susceptibility Domain
definition: This includes microbiology susceptibility test results, plus results of any other organism-related tests.

label: Organ Measurement Domain
definition: Findings from organ measurement evaluations.

label: Pharmacokinetic Concentration Domain
definition: Concentrations of drugs/metabolites in fluids or tissues as a function of time.

label: Physical Exam Domain
definition: Findings collected during a physical examination of the subject. It has findings that are discovered that are related to body systems. Does not include vital signs measurements, which are stored in the vital signs domain.

label: Pharmacogenomics Domain
definition: Pharmacogenomics findings that initially focus on genotype and gene expression data.

label: Pharmacokinetic Parameters Domain
definition: Pharmacokinetic parameters derived from pharmacokinetic concentration-time (PC) data.

label: Questionnaire Domain
definition: Questionnaire data may include, but are not limited to the following: subject reported outcomes, validated or non-validated questionnaires, and validated or non-validated diaries (i.e. data with a common topicality).

label: Subject Characteristics Domain
definition: The subject characteristics domain is for data not collected in other domains that is subject-related. Examples: subject initials, other race details, eye color, childbearing status, etc.

label: Subject Element Domain
definition: The subject element table describes the actual order of elements followed by the subject, together with the start date/time and end date/time for each element.

label: Surgery Domain
definition: Surgical information.

label: Skin Test Domain
definition: Findings from diagnostic skin tests.

label: Sleep Polysomnography Domain
definition: Findings from diagnostic sleep tests (polysomnography).

label: Stress Exercise Test Data Domain
definition: Findings from exercise stress tests.

label: Substance Use Domain
definition: The intent of the domain is to capture substance use information that may be used to assess the efficacy and/or safety of therapies that look to mitigate the effects of chronic substance use.

label: Subject Visits Domain
definition: The subject visits table describes the actual start and end data/time for each visit of each individual subject.

label: Trial Arms Domain
definition: The trial arms table describes each planned arm in the trial. An arm is described as an ordered sequence of elements.

label: Trial Elements Domain
definition: The trial elements table describes the element code that is unique for each element, the element description, and the rules for starting and ending an element.

label: Trial Inclusion and Exclusion Criteria Domain
pref_label: Trial Inclusion and Exclusion Criteria Domain
definition: The trial summary information domain is not subject oriented. It contains one record for each of the inclusion and exclusion criteria for the trial.

label: Trial Summary Domain
definition: The trial summary information domain is not subject oriented. It contains one record for each trial summary characteristic.

label: Trial Visits Domain
definition: The trial visits table describes the planned order and number of visits in the study within each arm.

label: Vital Signs Domain
definition: Measurements including but not limited to blood pressure, temperature, respiration, body surface area, BMI, height and weight.

label: Trial Blinding Schema
pref_label: CDISC SDTM Trial Blinding Schema Terminology
definition: The name of a code list that contains terms to define the type of blinding for the trial. (NCI)

label: Double Blind Study
definition: A study in which neither the subject nor the investigator nor the research team interacting with the subject or data during the trial knows what treatment a subject is receiving. (CDISC glossary)

label: Open Label Study
definition: A trial in which subjects and investigators know which product each subject is receiving; opposite of a blinded or double-blind study. (CDISC glossary)

label: Single Blind Study
definition: A study in which one party, either the investigator or the subject, does not know which medication or placebo is administered to the subject; also called singlemasked study. (CDISC glossary)

label: Trial Indication Type
pref_label: CDISC SDTM Trial Indication Type Terminology
definition: The name of a code list that contains terms to define the type of trial, e.g. cure or prevention. (NCI)

label: Cure Study
definition: A type of study protocol designed to evaluate intervention(s) aimed to cure a disease or condition.  (NCI)

label: Diagnosis Study
definition: A type of study protocol designed to evaluate intervention(s) aimed at identifying a disease or condition.  (NCI)

label: Adverse Effect Mitigation Study
definition: A type of study designed to identify actions necessary to eliminate or reduce the risk to human life or well-being as a result of a particular medication or treatment regimen.  (NCI)

label: Prevention Study
definition: A type of study designed to identify actions necessary to permanently eliminate or reduce the long-term risk to human life as a result of a particular medication or treatment regimen.

label: Treatment Study
definition: A type of study protocol designed to evaluate intervention(s) for treatment of disease, syndrome or condition.

label: Trial Phase
definition: Clinical trials are broken into three or four phases: Phase I tests a new drug or treatment for safety in a small group; Phase II expands the study to a larger group of people; Phase III expands the study to an even larger group of people to measure whether the treatment actually benefits patients, and whether its benefits exceed its risks; and Phase IV takes place after the drug or treatment has been licensed and marketed. (NCI)

label: Phase I Trial
definition: The initial introduction of an investigational new drug into humans. Phase 1 studies are typically closely monitored and may be conducted in patients or normal volunteer subjects. NOTE: These studies are designed to determine the metabolism and pharmacologic actions of the drug in humans, the side effects associated with increasing doses, and, if possible, to gain early evidence on effectiveness. During Phase 1, sufficient information about the drug’s pharmacokinetics and pharmacological effects should be obtained to permit the design of well-controlled, scientifically valid, Phase 2 studies. The total number of subjects and patients included in Phase I studies varies with the drug, but is generally in the range of 20 to 80. Phase 1 studies also include studies of drug metabolism, structure-activity relationships, and mechanism of action in humans, as well as studies in which investigational drugs are used as research tools to explore biological phenomena or disease processes.  [After FDA CDER Handbook, ICH E8] (CDISC glossary)

label: Phase I/II Trial
definition: A class of clinical study that combines elements characteristic of traditional Phase I and Phase II trials. See also Phase I, Phase II.

label: Phase II Trial
definition: Phase 2. Controlled clinical studies conducted to evaluate the effectiveness of the drug for a particular indication or indications in patients with the disease or condition under study and to determine the common short-term side effects and risks associated with the drug. NOTE: Phase 2 studies are typically well controlled, closely monitored, and conducted in a relatively small number of patients, usually involving no more than several hundred subjects. [After FDA CDER Handbook, ICH E8]  (CDISC glossary)

label: Phase II/III Trial
definition: A class of clinical study that combines elements characteristic of traditional Phase II and Phase III trials.

label: Phase IIa Trial
definition: A clinical research protocol generally refered to as a pilot or feasibility trial that aims to prove the concept of the new intervention in question. (NCI)

label: Phase IIb Trial
definition: A clinical research protocol generally refered to as a well-controlled and pivotal trial that aims to prove the mechanism of action of the new intervention in question. A pivotal study will generally be well-controlled, randomized, of adequate size, and whenever possible, double-blind. (NCI)

label: Phase III Trial
definition: Phase 3. Studies are expanded controlled and uncontrolled trials. They are performed after preliminary evidence suggesting effectiveness of the drug has been obtained, and are intended to gather the additional information about effectiveness and safety that is needed to confirm efficacy and evaluate the overall benefit–risk relationship of the drug and to provide an adequate basis for physician labeling. NOTE: Phase 3 studies usually include from several hundred to several thousand subjects. [After FDA CDER Handbook, ICH E8]  (CDISC glossary)

label: Phase IIIa Trial
definition: A classification typically assigned retrospectively to a Phase III trial upon determination by regulatory authorities of a need for a Phase III B trial.

label: Phase IIIb Trial
definition: A subcategory of Phase III trials done near the time of approval to elicit additional findings. NOTE: Dossier review may continue while associated Phase IIIB trials are conducted. These trials may be required as a condition of regulatory authority approval.

label: Phase IV Trial
definition: Phase 4. Postmarketing (Phase 4) studies to delineate additional information about the drug’s risks, benefits, and optimal use that may be requested by regulatory authorities in conjunction with marketing approval. NOTE: These studies could include, but would not be limited to, studying different doses or schedules of administration than were used in Phase 2 studies, use of the drug in other patient populations or other stages of the disease, or use of the drug over a longer period of time. [After FDA CDER Handbook, ICH E8]  (CDISC glossary)

label: Phase V Trial
definition: Postmarketing surveillance is sometimes referred to as Phase V.

label: Not Applicable
definition: Determination of a value is not relevant in the current context. (NCI)

label: Trial Summary Parameter Test Code
pref_label: CDISC SDTM Trial Summary Parameter Terminology by Code
definition: Individual characteristics of a clinical trial, e.g. description of trial design, trial blinding schema, and primary objective of trial. (NCI)

label: Test Product Added to Existing Treatment
pref_label: Test Product Added to Existing Treatment
definition: The addition of a therapeutic product to the existing regimen in a clinical trial, where both entities remain as discrete products.

label: Adverse Event Dictionary
definition: A reference source that provides meanings of words related to adverse events. (NCI)

label: Planned Maximum Age of Subjects
definition: The anticipated maximum age of the subjects to be entered in a clinical trial. (NCI)

label: Planned Minimum Age of Subjects
definition: The anticipated minimum age of the subjects to be entered in a clinical trial. (NCI)

label: Age Group
definition: Subgroups of populations based on age. (NCI)

label: Age Unit
definition: Those units of time that are routinely used to express the age of a person. (NCI)

label: Dose
definition: The amount of drug administered to a patient or test subject at one time or the total quantity administered. [AMA Manual of Style] (CDISC Glossary)

label: Drug Dictionary
definition: A reference source that provides meanings of words related to drugs. (NCI)

label: Trial Length
definition: The anticipated length of a clinical trial measured as a unit of time. (NCI)

label: Medical History Dictionary
definition: A reference source that provides meanings of words related to medical history. (NCI)

label: Planned Subject Number
definition: The number of subjects entered in a clinical trial. (NCI)

label: Randomization
definition: The process of assigning trial subjects to treatment or control groups using an element of chance to determine the assignments in order to reduce bias. NOTE: Unequal randomization is used to allocate subjects into groups at a differential rate; for example, three subjects may be assigned to a treatment group for every one assigned to the control group. [ICH E6 1.48] See also balanced study. (CDISC glossary)

label: Route of Administration
definition: The course by which a substance was administered in order to reach the site of action in the body.

label: Sex of Study Group
definition: The specific sex, either male, female, or mixed of the subject group being studied. (NCI)

label: Study Stop Rules
definition: The rule, regulation and/or condition that determines the point in time when a clinical trial will be terminated. (NCI)

label: Trial Blinding Schema
definition: The name of a code list that contains terms to define the type of blinding for the trial. (NCI)

label: Control Type
definition: Comparator against which the study treatment is evaluated (e.g., concurrent (placebo, no treatment, dose-response, active), external (historical, published literature).

label: Diagnosis Group
definition: A grouping of individuals on the basis of a shared procedure or disease, or lack thereof (e.g. healthy volunteers, type 2 diabetic subjects, subjects with renal cell cancer).  Standardized naming systems are available that define the groups within which a subject should be placed. (NCI)

label: Trial Indication Type
definition: The name of a code list that contains terms to define the type of trial, e.g. cure or prevention.  (NCI)

label: Trial Title
definition: The name of a clinical trial. (NCI)

label: Trial Phase
definition: Clinical trials are broken into three or four phases: Phase I tests a new drug or treatment for safety in a small group; Phase II expands the study to a larger group of people; Phase III expands the study to an even larger group of people to measure whether the treatment actually benefits patients, and whether its benefits exceed its risks; and Phase IV takes place after the drug or treatment has been licensed and marketed. (NCI)

label: Trial Type
definition: The type of clinical trial performed e.g. efficacy, safety. (NCI)

label: Trial Summary Parameter Test Name
pref_label: CDISC SDTM Trial Summary Parameter Terminology by Name
definition: Individual characteristics of a clinical trial, e.g. description of trial design, trial blinding schema, and primary objective of trial. (NCI)

label: Test Product Added to Existing Treatment
pref_label: Test Product Added to Existing Treatment
definition: The addition of a therapeutic product to the existing regimen in a clinical trial, where both entities remain as discrete products.

definition: A reference source that provides meanings of words related to adverse events. (NCI)

definition: The anticipated maximum age of the subjects to be entered in a clinical trial. (NCI)

label: Planned Minimum Age of Subjects
definition: The anticipated minimum age of the subjects to be entered in a clinical trial. (NCI)

definition: Subgroups of populations based on age. (NCI)

(NCI)

label: Trial Type
definition: The type of clinical trial performed e.g. efficacy, safety. (NCI)

label: Trial Type
definition: The type of clinical trial performed e.g. efficacy, safety. (NCI)

label: Bioavailability Study
definition: A study of the degree to which or rate at which a drug or other substance is absorbed or becomes available at the site of physiological activity after administration. (NCI)

label: Therapeutic Equivalency Study
definition: A study most often used to compare the efficacy of different formulations to treat a given disease.  It is the testing of an old versus a new formulation in healthy volunteers or subjects with the disease under study and usually in one dose. (NCI)

label: Efficacy Study
definition: A study of the relative therapeutic efficacy of treatment of a disease. Usually this is a Phase II or III study. (NCI)

label: Pharmacodynamic Study
definition: A study of the biochemical and physiological effect of a drug and the mechanism of drug action and the relationship between drug concentration and effect. (NCI)

label: Pharmacoeconomic Study
definition: A study that assesses the value associated with a given drug in therapeutic and economic terms. This type of study is multidisciplinary in nature and takes into consideration the social and economic costs (resource utilization costs including direct, indirect, and intangible costs) of drug therapy in addition to its direct therapeutic benefits. Analyses relate the difference in therapeutic benefits to the difference in costs between treatment alternatives. (NCI)

label: Pharmacogenomic Study
definition: A study of identification and analysis of genomic variations that affect the efficacy of a drug. Pharmacogenomic studies can potentially be predictive of an individual's drug-response or adverse reactions or susceptibility to iatrogenic disorders, and may also reveal new targets that can help in the design of new drugs. (NCI)

label: Pharmacokinetic Study
definition: A study of the process by which a drug is absorbed, distributed, metabolized, and eliminated by the body. (NCI)

label: Safety Study
definition: A study of the relative safety of treatment of a disease. Usually this is a Phase I or II trial. (NCI)

label: Units for Vital Signs Results
pref_label: CDISC SDTM Unit for Vital Sign Result Terminology
definition: The unit used to record and describe the result of a test investigating a vital sign. (NCI)

label: Percentage
definition: A fraction or ratio with 100 understood as the denominator. (NCI)

label: Beats per Minute
definition: The number of heartbeats measured per minute time. (NCI)

label: Breaths per Minute
definition: The number of breaths (inhalation and exhalation) taken per minute time. (NCI)

label: Degree Celsius
definition: A unit of temperature of the temperature scale designed so that the freezing point of water is 0 degrees and the boiling point is 100 degrees at standard atmospheric pressure. The current official definition of the Celsius sets 0.01 C to be at the triple point of water and a degree to be 1/273.16 of the difference in temperature between the triple point of water and absolute zero. One degree Celsius represents the same temperature difference as one Kelvin. (NCI)

label: Centimeter
definition: A basic unit of length in the former CGS version of metric system, equal to one hundredth of a meter or approximately 0.393 700 787 inch. (NCI)

label: Degree Fahrenheit
definition: The Fahrenheit temperature scale is named after the German physicist Gabriel Fahrenheit (1686-1736), who proposed it in 1724.  In this scale, the freezing point of water is 32 degrees Fahrenheit and the boiling point is 212 degrees, placing the boiling and melting points of water 180 degrees apart. In this scale a degree Fahrenheit is 5/9ths of a kelvin (or of a degree Celsius), and minus 40 degrees Fahrenheit is equal to minus 40 degrees Celsius. (NCI)

label: Gram
definition: A metric unit of mass equal to one one thousandth of a kilogram. (NCI)

label: Inch
definition: A traditional unit of length equal to 2.54 centimeters. (NCI)

label: Kilogram
definition: The basic SI unit of mass.  It is defined as the mass of an international prototype in the form of a platinum-iridium cylinder kept at Sevres in France. It is the only basic unit still defined in terms of a material object, and also the only one with a prefix [kilo] already in place. A kilogram is equal to 1,000 grams and 2.204 622 6 pounds. (NCI)

label: Kilogram Per Square Meter
definition: The SI derived unit of spread rate of a substance by mass, used also as a measure of area density. (NCI)

label: Pound
definition: A traditional unit of mass. By international agreement, one avoirdupois pound is equal to exactly 0.453 592 37 kilogram, 16 ounces, or 1.215 28 troy pounds. (NCI)

label: Square Meter
definition: The SI unit of area measurement equal to a square whose sides are one meter long. Square meter is equal to 10,000 square centimeters; 0.01 ares; 1.196 square yards; 10.76 square feet; 1550 square inches. (NCI)

label: Millimeter of Mercury
definition: A unit of pressure equal to 0.001316 atmosphere and equal to the pressure indicated by one millimeter rise of mercury in a barometer at the Earth's surface. (NCI)

label: Ohm
definition: A unit of electrical resistance equal to the resistance between two points on a conductor when a potential difference of one volt between them produces a current of one ampere. Ohm is also used to measure impedance and reactance for complex resistance. A measurement in ohms is the reciprocal of a measurement in siemens. (NCI)

label: Vital Signs Test Code
pref_label: CDISC SDTM Vital Sign Terminology by Code
definition: The name given to the test that analyzes a particular set of vital signs including temperature, respiratory rate, heart beat (pulse), and blood pressure. (NCI)

label: Body Mass Index
definition: A general indicator of the body fat an individual is carrying based upon the ratio of weight to height. (NCI)

label: Adipose Tissue
definition: A specialized form of connective tissue consisting primarily of adipocytes (fat cells), surrounded by a meshwork of collagen fibers.

label: Body Surface Area
definition: A measure of the 2-dimensional extent of the body surface (i.e., the skin).  Body surface area (BSA) can be calculated by mathematical formula or from a chart that relates height to weight.  BSA is often an important factor in dosing. (NCI)

label: Diastolic Blood Pressure
definition: The blood pressure after the contraction of the heart while the chambers of the heart refill with blood. (NCI)

label: Body Frame Size
definition: The categorization of a person's body frame into small, medium and large based on the measurement of wrist circumference or the breadth of the elbow. (NCI)

label: Height
definition: The vertical measurement or distance from the base to the top of an object; the vertical dimension of extension. (NCI)

label: Heart Rate
definition: The number of heartbeats per unit of time, usually expressed as beats per minute. (NCI)

label: Mean Arterial Pressure
definition: The mean pressure of the blood within the arterial circulation. The arterial pressure may be directly measured by insertion of an intra-arterial catheter connected to a transducer. The mean arterial pressure (MAP) can be calculated by subsequent analysis of the waveform. MAP can be approximated without an invasive procedure using the following formula: diastolic pressure plus 1/3 of the pulse pressure, where pulse pressure is systolic pressure - diastolic pressure. (NCI)

label: Pulse Rate
definition: The rate of the pulse as observed in an artery, expressed as beats per minute. It can be measured at several anatomical sites, including the wrist, neck, temple, groin, behind the knees, or on top of the foot. (NCI)

label: Respiratory Rate
definition: The rate of breathing (inhalation and exhalation) measured within in a unit time, usually expressed as breaths per minute. (NCI)

label: Systolic Blood Pressure
definition: The blood pressure during the contraction of the left ventricle of the heart.

label: Temperature
definition: The property of a body or region of space that determines whether or not there will be a net flow of heat into it or out of it from a neighboring body or region and in which direction (if any) the heat will flow, perceptible by living organism as a somatic sensation of cold or heat. It is a measure of the average translational kinetic energy associated with the disordered microscopic motion of atoms and molecules. Temperature is measured in one of the three standard temperature scales: Celsius, Kelvin, and Fahrenheit. (NCI)

label: Weight
definition: The vertical force exerted by a mass as a result of gravity. (NCI)

label: Vital Signs Test Name
pref_label: CDISC SDTM Vital Sign Terminology  by Name
definition: The name given to the test that analyzes a particular set of vital signs including temperature, respiratory rate, heart beat (pulse), and blood pressure. (NCI)

label: Body Mass Index
definition: A general indicator of the body fat an individual is carrying based upon the ratio of weight to height. (NCI)

label: Body Frame Size
definition: The categorization of a person's body frame into small, medium and large based on the measurement of wrist circumference or the breadth of the elbow. (NCI)

label: Height
definition: The vertical measurement or distance from the base to the top of an object; the vertical dimension of extension. (NCI)

label: Heart Rate
definition: The number of heartbeats per unit of time, usually expressed as beats per minute. (NCI)

The mean arterial pressure (MAP) can be calculated by subsequent analysis of the waveform. MAP can be approximated without an invasive procedure using the following formula: diastolic pressure plus 1/3 of the pulse pressure, where pulse pressure is systolic pressure - diastolic pressure. (NCI)

label: Pulse Rate

label: Respiratory Rate
definition: The rate of breathing (inhalation and exhalation) measured within in a unit time, usually expressed as breaths per minute. (NCI)

label: Systolic Blood Pressure
definition: The blood pressure during the contraction of the left ventricle of the heart.

It is a measure of the average translational kinetic energy associated with the disordered microscopic motion of atoms and molecules. Temperature is measured in one of the three standard temperature scales: Celsius, Kelvin, and Fahrenheit. (NCI)

label: Weight
definition: The vertical force exerted by a mass as a result of gravity. (NCI)

label: No Yes Response
pref_label: CDISC SDTM Yes No Unknown or Not Applicable Response Terminology
definition: A term that is used to indicate a question with permissible values of yes/no/unknown/not applicable.

label: No
definition: The non-affirmative response to a question. (NCI)

label: Not Applicable
definition: Determination of a value is not relevant in the current context. (NCI)

label: Unknown
definition: Not known, not observed, not recorded, or refused. (NCI)

label: Yes
definition: The affirmative response to a question. (NCI)

label: Laboratory Test Code
pref_label: CDISC SDTM Laboratory Test Terminology by Code
definition: Terminology used for Laboratory Tests of the CDISC Standard Data Tabulation Model.

label: Anisocytosis
definition: A measurement of the inequality in the size of the red blood cells in a whole blood specimen.

label: Poikilocytosis
definition: A measurement of the odd-shaped erythrocytes in a whole blood specimen.

label: Total Bilirubin
definition: A measurement of the total bilirubin in a biological specimen.

label: Partial Thromboplastin Time
definition: A measurement of the length of time that it takes for clotting to occur when reagents are added to a plasma specimen. The test is partial due to the absence of tissue factor (Factor III) from the reaction mixture.

label: Plasma Glucose Measurement
definition: A measurement of the glucose in a biological specimen.

label: pH
definition: A measure of the acidity or alkalinity of a fluid on a scale of 0 to 14.

label: Erythrocyte Count
definition: A count of the total erythrocytes per unit of a biological specimen.

label: Reticulocyte Count
definition: A count of the reticulocytes per unit of a biological specimen.

label: Leukocyte Count
definition: A count of the leukocytes per unit of a biological specimen.

label: Lymphocyte Count
definition: A count of the lymphocytes per unit of a biological specimen.

label: Platelet Count
definition: A count of the platelets per unit of a biological specimen.

label: Blood Urea Nitrogen Measurement
definition: A measurement of the urea nitrogen in a blood specimen.

label: Serum Total Cholesterol Measurement
definition: A measurement of the cholesterol in a biological specimen.

label: Serum HDL Cholesterol Measurement
definition: A measurement of the high density lipoprotein cholesterol in a biological specimen.

label: Serum LDL Cholesterol Measurement
definition: A measurement of the low density lipoprotein cholesterol in a biological specimen.

label: Prothrombin Time
definition: A blood clotting measurement that evaluates the extrinsic pathway of coagulation and is expressed in units of time or percent activity.

label: Absolute Neutrophil Count
definition: A count of the neutrophils per unit of a biological specimen.

label: Albumin Measurement
definition: A measurement of the albumin protein in a biological specimen.

label: Alkaline Phosphatase Measurement
definition: A measurement of the alkaline phosphatase in a biological specimen.

label: Alanine Aminotransferase Measurement
definition: A measurement of the alanine aminotransferase in a biological specimen.

label: Amylase Measurement
definition: A measurement of the pancreatic enzyme amylase in a biological specimen.

label: Aspartate Aminotransferase Measurement
definition: A measurement of the aspartate aminotransferase in a biological specimen.

label: Bacterial Count
definition: A measurement of the bacteria in a biological specimen.

label: Total Basophil Count
definition: A count of the basophils per unit of a biological specimen.

label: Basophil To Leukocyte Ratio
definition: A relative measure (ratio or percentage) of the basophils to leukocytes in a biological specimen.

label: Direct Bilirubin Measurement
definition: A measurement of the conjugated or water-soluble bilirubin in a biological specimen.

label: Indirect Bilirubin Measurement
definition: A measurement of the unconjugated or non-water-soluble bilirubin in a biological specimen.

label: Blast To Leukocyte Ratio
definition: A relative measure (ratio or percentage) of the blasts to leukocytes in a biological specimen.

label: Calcium Measurement
definition: A measurement of the calcium in a biological specimen.

label: Creatine Kinase Measurement
definition: A measurement of the total creatine kinase in a biological specimen.

label: Creatine Kinase BB Measurement
definition: A measurement of the homozygous B-type creatine kinase in a biological specimen.

label: Creatine Kinase MB Measurement
definition: A measurement of the heterozygous MB-type creatine kinase in a biological specimen.

label: Creatine Kinase MM Measurement
definition: A measurement of the homozygous M-type creatine kinase in a biological specimen.

label: Chloride Measurement
definition: A measurement of the chloride in a biological specimen.

label: Carbon Dioxide Measurement
definition: A measurement of the carbon dioxide gas in a biological specimen.

label: Color Assessment
definition: A measurement of the color of a biological specimen.

label: Creatinine Measurement
definition: A measurement of the creatinine in a biological specimen.

label: C-Reactive Protein Measurement
definition: A measurement of the C reactive protein in a biological specimen.

label: Elliptocyte Count
definition: A count of the elliptocytes per unit of a biological specimen.

label: Eosinophil Count
definition: A count of the eosinophils per unit of a biological specimen.

label: Eosinophil To Leukocyte Ratio
definition: A relative measure (ratio or percentage) of the eosinophils to leukocytes in a biological specimen.

label: Epithelial Cell Count
definition: A measurement of the epithelial cells in a biological specimen.

label: Fibrinogen Measurement
definition: A measurement of the fibrinogen in a biological specimen.

label: Hematocrit
definition: The percentage of a whole blood specimen that is composed of red blood cells (erythrocytes).

label: Erythrocyte Mean Corpuscular Hemoglobin
definition: A quantitative measurement of the mean amount of hemoglobin per erythrocyte in a biological specimen.

label: Erythrocyte Mean Corpuscular Hemoglobin Concentration
definition: A quantitative measurement of the mean amount of hemoglobin per erythrocytes in a specified volume of a biological specimen.

label: Erythrocyte Mean Corpuscular Volume
definition: A quantitative measurement of the mean volume of erythrocytes in a biological specimen.

label: Erythrocyte Distribution Width Measurement
definition: A value derived from mean corpuscular volume and the standard deviation of the red blood cell volume in a whole blood specimen.

label: Dacryocyte Analysis
definition: A count of dacryocytes in unit of a biological specimen.

label: Hypochromia
definition: An observation which indicates that the hemoglobin concentration in a red blood cell specimen has fallen below a specified level.

label: Polychromasia
definition: A measurement of the blue-staining characteristic of newly generated erythrocytes.

label: International Normalized Ratio of Prothrombin Time
pref_label: International Normalized Ratio of Prothrombin Time
definition: A ratio that represents the prothrombin time for a plasma specimen, divided by the result for a control plasma specimen, further standardized for the International Sensitivity Index of the tissue factor (thromboplastin) used in the test.

label: Serum VLDL Cholesterol Measurement
definition: A measurement of the very low density lipoprotein cholesterol in a biological specimen.

label: Triacylglycerol Lipase Measurement
definition: A measurement of the pancreatic lipase in a biological specimen.

label: Sodium Measurement
definition: A measurement of the sodium in a biological specimen.

label: Nitrite Measurement
definition: A measurement of the nitrite in a urine specimen.

label: Triglyceride Measurement
definition: A measurement of the triglycerides in a biological specimen.

label: Thyrotropin Measurement
definition: A measurement of the thyrotropin in a biological specimen.

label: Urate Measurement
definition: A measurement of the urate in a biological specimen.

label: Urea Measurement
definition: A measurement of the urea in a biological specimen.

label: Urobilinogen Measurement
definition: A measurement of the urobilinogen in a biological specimen.

label: Vitamin B12 Measurement
definition: A measurement of the Vitamin B12 in a serum specimen.

label: Atypical Lymphocyte Count
definition: A count of the atypical lymphocytes per unit of a biological specimen.

label: Atypical Lymphocyte To Leukocyte Ratio
definition: A relative measure (ratio or percentage) of the atypical lymphocytes to leukocytes in a biological specimen.

label: Lymphocyte To Leukocyte Ratio
definition: A relative measure (ratio or percentage) of the lymphocytes to leukocytes in a biological specimen.

label: Macrocyte Count
definition: A count of the macrocytes per unit of a biological specimen.

label: Microcyte Count
definition: A count of the microcytes per unit of a biological specimen.

label: Monocyte Count
definition: A count of the monocytes per unit of a biological specimen.

label: Monocyte To Leukocyte Ratio
definition: A relative measure (ratio or percentage) of the monocytes to leukocytes in a biological specimen.

label: Myeloblast To Leukocyte Ratio
definition: A relative measure (ratio or percentage) of the myeloblasts to leukocytes in a biological specimen.

label: Myelocyte To Leukocyte Ratio
definition: A relative measure (ratio or percentage) of the myelocytes to leukocytes in a biological specimen.

label: Neutrophil To Leukocyte Ratio
definition: The determination of the ratio of neutrophils compared to leukocytes in a blood sample. The measurement may be expressed as a ratio or percentage.

label: Reticulocyte To Erythrocyte Ratio
definition: A relative measure (ratio or percentage) of reticulocytes to erythrocytes in a biological specimen.

label: Prolymphocyte To Leukocyte Ratio
definition: A relative measure (ratio or percentage) of prolymphocytes to leukocytes in a biological specimen.

label: Neutrophil Band Form Count
definition: A count of the banded neutrophils per unit of a biological specimen.

label: Neutrophil Band Form To Leukocyte Ratio
pref_label: Neutrophil Band Form To Leukocyte Ratio
definition: A relative measure (ratio or percentage) of the banded neutrophils to leukocytes in a biological specimen.

label: Specific Gravity
definition: A ratio of the density of a fluid to the density of water.

label: Magnesium Measurement
definition: A measurement of the magnesium in a biological specimen.

label: Gamma Glutamyl Transpeptidase Measurement
definition: A measurement of the gamma glutamyl transpeptidase in a biological specimen.

label: Hemoglobin Measurement
definition: A measurement of the hemoglobin in a biological specimen.

label: Glycosylated Hemoglobin Measurement
definition: A measurement of the glycosylated hemoglobin in a biological specimen.

label: Hepatitis B Virus Surface Antigen Measurement
pref_label: Hepatitis B Virus Surface Antigen Measurement
definition: A measurement of the surface antigen reaction of a biological specimen to the Hepatitis B virus.

label: Choriogonadotropin Beta Measurement
definition: A measurement of the Choriogonadotropin Beta in a biological specimen.

label: Potassium Measurement
definition: A measurement of the potassium in a biological specimen.

label: Ketone Measurement
definition: A measurement of the ketones in a biological specimen.

label: Lactate Dehydrogenase Measurement
definition: A measurement of the lactate dehydrogenase in a biological specimen.

label: Leukocyte Esterase Measurement
definition: A measurement of the enzyme which indicates the presence of white blood cells in a biological specimen.

label: Phosphate Measurement
definition: A measurement of the phosphate in a biological specimen.

label: Total Protein Measurement
definition: A measurement of a group of complex organic macromolecules composed of one or more alpha-L-amino acid chains in a biological specimen.

pref_label: CDISC SDTM Laboratory Test Terminology by Name
definition: Terminology used for Laboratory Tests of the CDISC Standard Data Tabulation Model.

definition: A measurement of the inequality in the size of the red blood cells in a whole blood specimen.

definition: A measurement of the odd-shaped erythrocytes in a whole blood specimen.
